title: Ask HN: What's the best way to attract new readers to my content?
text:
I run a website/digital magazine about a specific topic and I want to attract new readers. It is free to read and there are no ads, so I am not doing this for money.

I tried with Facebook and Instagram ads, and running giveaways, but nothing worked as expected.

Does anynone have any suggestion? I can invest on this (I paid for ads and giveaways prizes), but I'd like to try something new and not the same things that don't work.

Online signup and then forced phone cancellation is an infuriating pattern
text:
I just got off the phone with the Wall Street Journal. They have no option to cancel online, even though I signed up online. Forcing me to call a phone number to cancel my subscription so you can put me through a sales pipeline will turn me off your service forever. I might have renewed my subscription to the WSJ at some point, but no longer.

If you run an online subscription service, don't be like the WSJ.

Ask HN: Best practices for technical SEO for domains with more than 100k pages?
text:
By "technical SEO" I mean SEO problems that require software development.

What's special about domains with 100,000+ pages (e.g. niche search engines and large e-commerce sites) is that most basic SEO advice is necessary but far from sufficient.

I'm on a project with 1,000,000 pages and only about 50,000 are indexed. My "crawl budget" is absolutely small, but relatively large. How do I make sure the "right" content gets indexed? How does Google even define "right"?

I seem to be writing a lot of code to answer basic question like "which of my 1,000,000 pages are indexed?" and "which pages should I be actively seeking to index and de-index?"

If you work on "technical SEO" for something like Stack Overflow or Amazon I'd love to learn from you.

And if these are the wrong questions to ask, I'd especially like to learn from you.
